## Route 495

### Lincoln Tunnel Approach

The asphalt artery known as [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) slices through [Hudson County, New Jersey](/Hudson_County,_New_Jersey), not as a scenic byway, but as a relentless, 3.45-mile (5.55 km) conduit of human endeavor and perpetual motion. It’s less a road and more a necessity, a concrete umbilical cord connecting the industrial grit of [Secaucus](/Secaucus,_New_Jersey) to the glittering, perpetually demanding heart of [Midtown Manhattan](/Midtown_Manhattan). This isn't a route for leisurely drives; it's a funnel, expertly engineered and perpetually overwhelmed, designed to shunt the daily tide of commuters and commerce into the yawning maw of the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel).

Maintained with a tripartite burden by the [New Jersey Turnpike Authority](/New_Jersey_Turnpike_Authority) (NJTA), the [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation) (NJDOT), and the venerable [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey) (PANYNJ), this critical [freeway](/Controlled-access_highway) has existed in various forms since 1937, though its current designation solidified in 1959. It serves as the indispensable link between [Interstate 95](/Interstate_95_in_New_Jersey) (the omnipresent [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike)) at its exits 16E-17 in [Secaucus](/Secaucus,_New_Jersey) and its counterpart, [New York State Route 495](/New_York_State_Route_495) (NY 495), at the [New York](/New_York_(state)) state line, deep within the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) itself. A crucial caveat, perhaps a minor mercy, is the restriction on [hazardous goods](/Dangerous_goods) within the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel), preventing an already precarious situation from becoming a genuine catastrophe.

Along its relatively brief but intensely vital span, [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) intersects with several other major arteries that feed its insatiable appetite for traffic. Notable junctions include [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9) and [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) in [North Bergen](/North_Bergen,_New_Jersey), as well as [County Route 501](/County_Route_501_(New_Jersey)) in [Union City](/Union_City,_New_Jersey). These intersections are less graceful merges and more strategic choke points, meticulously designed to manage the immense flow.

Geographically, [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) is entirely contained within [Hudson County](/Hudson_County,_New_Jersey), [New Jersey](/New_Jersey), a densely populated region where concrete often outweighs greenery. It is classified under the [New Jersey State Highway Routes](/State_highways_in_New_Jersey) system, alongside its more expansive [Interstate](/List_of_Interstate_Highways_in_New_Jersey), [U.S.](/List_of_U.S._Routes_in_New_Jersey), and [State](/List_of_state_highways_in_New_Jersey) siblings, though it notably lacks the leisure of being a [Scenic Byway](/List_of_New_Jersey_Scenic_Byways). Indeed, the only "scenic" aspect is the distant, often-mocked skyline, a cruel taunt for those trapped in its embrace. Its numerical designation places it between [Route 446X](/New_Jersey_Route_446X) and [I-676](/Interstate_676_(New_Jersey)) in the grand, bewildering tapestry of New Jersey's highway network.

This essential stretch of road is primarily a six-lane [freeway](/Controlled-access_highway), distinguished by a [reversible](/Reversible_lane) bus lane, a truly inspired piece of engineering that transforms the daily morning commute into a slightly less soul-crushing experience for bus passengers. This dedicated lane, which extends the entire length of the freeway and plunges into the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel)'s center tube, is a testament to the sheer volume of humanity attempting to reach Manhattan each weekday.

### Route description

The eastbound journey on [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) commences, not with a flourish, but with the pragmatic efficiency of an off-ramp from the northbound lanes of the [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike). This initial segment, near the nebulous boundary separating [Secaucus](/Secaucus,_New_Jersey) and [North Bergen](/North_Bergen,_New_Jersey), immediately thrusts drivers into the heart of the matter. From this point, the main roadway, a formidable six-lane [freeway](/Controlled-access_highway), stretches eastward through [North Bergen](/North_Bergen,_New_Jersey), its maintenance falling under the purview of the [New Jersey Turnpike Authority](/New_Jersey_Turnpike_Authority) (NJTA).

A pivotal, often chaotic, point along this route is the interchange with [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3). For eastbound travelers, this junction provides crucial access to eastbound [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) and the sprawling expanse of [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9) (US 1/9). Conversely, westbound drivers can access westbound [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) here. This intersection is a major nexus, a veritable circulatory pump for commuters, many of whom utilize [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) as their primary conduit to [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) and, ultimately, the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel). It’s a triangular ballet of vehicles, though direct access to [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9) from [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) is notably absent, forcing drivers to navigate the [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) exit as an intermediary step – a design choice that adds a certain layer of complexity, as if the commute wasn't already challenging enough.

Beyond this intricate interchange, [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) transitions into a segment maintained by the [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation) (NJDOT). Here, the freeway gracefully, or perhaps defiantly, crosses over the rail lines of the [New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway](/New_York,_Susquehanna_and_Western_Railway)'s New Jersey Subdivision and [Conrail Shared Assets Operations](/Conrail_Shared_Assets_Operations)' [Northern Branch](/Northern_Branch). Shortly thereafter, it encounters [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9) once more, this time in a partial interchange offering a westbound exit and an eastbound entrance.

The journey continues, leading to an interchange with [County Route 501](/County_Route_501_(New_Jersey)) (CR 501), more familiarly known as John F. Kennedy Boulevard. This intersection employs 30th and 31st Streets as efficient, if somewhat congested, [collector–distributor roads](/Collector%E2%80%93distributor_roads) to manage the local traffic flow. East of this junction, [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) plunges into [Union City](/Union_City,_New_Jersey), where it carves its path through a dense tapestry of residential areas, disappearing beneath a succession of overpasses that carry the city's grid of streets. The experience is one of constant motion, a relentless push through an urban canyon.

Upon entering [Weehawken](/Weehawken,_New_Jersey), the freeway presents a westbound exit and an eastbound entrance for Park Avenue, offering access to the charming, if somewhat congested, communities of [Weehawken](/Weehawken,_New_Jersey) and [Hoboken](/Hoboken,_New_Jersey). At this precise juncture, the maintenance responsibility for [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) shifts once more, this time to the formidable [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey) (PANYNJ), marking the final, most dramatic leg of the approach.

At this point, the highway embarks upon its most iconic and visually arresting feature: [The Helix](/Lincoln_Tunnel_Helix). This section, a local landmark, is an engineering marvel, a magnificent 360-degree looped [spiral bridge](/Spiral_bridge) that orchestrates the descent of [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) from the towering heights of the [New Jersey Palisades](/New_Jersey_Palisades) to the very entrance of the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) nestled beneath the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River). As the highway begins its spiral, it passes [Weehawken Stadium](/Weehawken,_New_Jersey) to its north and east, eventually disappearing beneath it as it approaches the tunnel's portal. This dizzying descent is not without its own dedicated access points, featuring a westbound exit and eastbound entrance for and from [County Route 677](/Boulevard_East) (John F. Kennedy/Hudson Boulevard East). Once it has shed the last of its surface connections, the road plunges definitively into the depths of the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel). At the precise midpoint of the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River), where the [New York](/New_York_(state)) state line is demarcated, [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) seamlessly transforms into [NY 495](/New_York_State_Route_495), a distinct entity from [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)), continuing its subterranean journey directly into the vibrant, often maddening, heart of [Midtown Manhattan](/Midtown_Manhattan) in [New York City](/New_York_City).

#### Exclusive Bus Lane (XBL)

Since 1970, a tactical, albeit temporary, transformation occurs during the morning rush hour: the leftmost of the three westbound lanes is commandeered for the "Exclusive Bus Lane" (XBL). This dedicated [bus lane](/Bus_lane) is a critical component of the region's transportation infrastructure, a testament to the sheer volume of commuters who choose, or are forced, to rely on public transit. The [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey) (PANYNJ) assumes the daily operational burden of the XBL, a role that encompasses everything from its timely opening and closing to the swift removal of any disabled vehicles and the immediate response to emergencies that inevitably arise.

This exclusive conduit is predominantly utilized by buses ferrying passengers eastward from the [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike) and [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3), with the vast majority heading towards the gargantuan [Port Authority Bus Terminal](/Port_Authority_Bus_Terminal) in Manhattan, a facility conveniently located just beyond the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) portals. On any given weekday morning, between the hours of 6 and 10 a.m., this single lane manages to accommodate over 1,800 buses and a staggering 65,000 bus commuters. Such figures firmly establish this [bus lane](/Bus_lane) as the busiest in the entire [United States](/United_States), a dubious honor that speaks volumes about the region's transportation challenges.

#### Lincoln Tunnel travel lanes

The [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) itself is a marvel of adaptable engineering, particularly its center tube, where each travel lane is ingeniously [reversible](/Reversible_lane). This flexibility is paramount to managing the ever-shifting tidal flows of trans-Hudson traffic. During the frenetic weekday morning rush hour, both lanes of the center tube, including the aforementioned exclusive bus lane, are dedicated to Manhattan-bound traffic, a desperate attempt to satiate the city's morning appetite for workers. Conversely, during the equally intense weekday evening rush hour, both lanes are flipped to serve New Jersey-bound traffic, disgorging the day's workforce back across the river. During less peak times, a more balanced approach is adopted, with one lane allocated for each direction. It's a delicate dance, a constant recalibration. Typically, New Jersey-bound traffic is channeled through both lanes of the north tube, while Manhattan-bound traffic is directed through both lanes of the south tube, creating a meticulously choreographed, if frequently strained, system of movement.

#### Traffic volume and congestion

[Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) is, by any measure, a perpetually inundated corridor. Its western terminus sees approximately 74,571 vehicles daily, a respectable, if not alarming, figure. However, by the time this torrent of traffic reaches the entrance of the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel), the volume swells dramatically to an astounding 119,432 vehicles. This exponential increase underscores the route's critical, yet overburdened, function.

The statistics, as always, paint a grim picture. According to the American Highway Users Alliance, as of their 2018 [update](/New_Jersey_Route_495), [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) holds the unenviable distinction of being one of the most severely congested corridors on the entire East Coast of the [United States](/United_States). Commuters, those poor souls, collectively squandered an estimated 3.4 million hours annually simply sitting in traffic along this route. It’s a statistic that perfectly encapsulates the cosmic weariness of modern existence, a monument to the futility of individual effort against systemic gridlock.

### History

#### Interstate 495

Initially, the approach to the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) was conceived and built as an integral part of the larger tunnel project. Its inaugural section, opening on December 22, 1937, coincided precisely with the completion of the tunnel's first (now the center) tube. This initial segment was a modest affair, extending only from the tunnel portal southward through the necessary [toll booths](/Toll_road) to a plaza that intersected with Park Avenue and Hudson County [Boulevard East](/Boulevard_East). To further facilitate local access, Marginal Street was also inaugurated at this time, enabling traffic from Hudson County [Boulevard East](/Boulevard_East) to proceed westward over Park Avenue to 32nd Street and the historic [Bergen Turnpike](/Bergen_Turnpike).

Just two years later, in 1939, the [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey) expanded this vital approach, extending it dramatically up the iconic [Helix](/Lincoln_Tunnel_Helix) and further west to connect with [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3). This expansion effectively designated the new stretch as an eastern extension of [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3), integrating it more fully into the nascent state highway system. The final piece of what would become modern-day [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) was unveiled on January 15, 1952, a date that marked the completion of the expansive [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike). This addition brought the turnpike interchange (Exit 16) into play, initially serving only [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) traffic traveling to and from the south, while Exit 17 catered to [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) traffic from the north.

With the ambitious genesis of the [Interstate Highway System](/Interstate_Highway_System) in 1956, the approach to the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) was earmarked for inclusion as an [Interstate Highway](/Interstate_Highway_System). Curiously, [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) itself, despite its critical role, was excluded from the Interstate network, primarily due to New Jersey's pragmatic, if somewhat reluctant, assessment that upgrading it to stringent [Interstate Highway standards](/Interstate_Highway_standards) would simply be too prohibitive in terms of cost. Nevertheless, the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) approach was indeed incorporated, and in 1959, it was officially renumbered from [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3) to [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)), a designation that, rather ironically, it did not fully meet in terms of Interstate standards at the time.

However, recognizing this discrepancy, the western segment of the newly minted [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)) was swiftly brought up to Interstate Highway standards through a series of improvements to its interchanges with both the [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike) and [Route 3](/New_Jersey_Route_3). The grand vision for [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)) was to create a seamless connection with [New York](/New_York_(state))'s own [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)) (the [Long Island Expressway](/Interstate_495_(New_York))) via the proposed [Mid-Manhattan Expressway](/Mid-Manhattan_Expressway). This ambitious [freeway](/Controlled-access_highway) through the very heart of [Midtown Manhattan](/Midtown_Manhattan) was, however, ultimately scuttled in 1971, falling victim to intense public opposition against a major highway bisecting the city's core.

The cancellation of the [Mid-Manhattan Expressway](/Mid-Manhattan_Expressway) meant that New Jersey's [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)) would forever remain disconnected from its New York counterpart. Consequently, the [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation) (NJDOT) began referring to the route simply as [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) starting in 1979, implicitly acknowledging the broken continuity. The [American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials](/American_Association_of_State_Highway_and_Transportation_Officials) (AASHTO) formally approved the decommissioning of the [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)) designation for the segment between [I-95](/Interstate_95_in_New_Jersey) and Pleasant Avenue/Park Avenue in [Union City](/Union_City,_New_Jersey) in 1980. Six years later, in 1986, AASHTO granted approval for the complete decommissioning of the remaining [I-495](/Interstate_495_(New_York)) designation within [New Jersey](/New_Jersey), cementing its status as a state route.

#### Historic Places eligibility

Perhaps ironically, given its utilitarian and often reviled nature, sections of [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495) have achieved a measure of historical recognition. Beginning with the [viaduct](/Viaduct) that gracefully, or perhaps grudgingly, spans the [Conrail](/Conrail) rail lines just west of [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9), the entire eastbound roadway has been deemed eligible for inclusion in the [New Jersey Register of Historic Places](/New_Jersey_Register_of_Historic_Places). This designation is a nod to its significant engineering, architectural design, and its undeniable historical impact. The eligibility was granted in a series of segmented approvals between 1991 and 2003, encompassing the entirety of the [Lincoln Tunnel Approach and Helix](/Lincoln_Tunnel_Helix), as well as the associated tunnels, [toll booths](/Toll_road), and even the ventilation towers – a testament to the comprehensive nature of the original construction. It seems even the most mundane infrastructure can, with enough time, acquire a patina of historical significance.

#### The Helix view and future

[The Helix](/Lincoln_Tunnel_Helix) has long been lauded, at least by those not entirely consumed by the existential dread of traffic, for providing a truly exceptional panoramic vista of the iconic [Manhattan skyline](/Skyline_of_New_York_City). This view, a fleeting moment of beauty amidst the concrete and exhaust fumes, has been fiercely protected by local zoning ordinances, which prohibit the construction of high-rise buildings that would dare to obstruct these precious sight-lines from higher vantage points within the town. However, even the best-laid plans of zoning boards are subject to the relentless march of development. As of June 2013, an [update](/New_Jersey_Route_495) revealed that the construction of a new residential building had already begun to partially obscure the once-unimpeded view from the lower portions of the roadway. It seems some things, like progress and the insatiable demand for real estate, are simply unstoppable.

Looking to the future, or rather, gazing into its inevitable decay, the [Port Authority of New York and New Jersey](/Port_Authority_of_New_York_and_New_Jersey) (PANYNJ) estimated in 2015 that [The Helix](/Lincoln_Tunnel_Helix) had a remaining working lifespan of a mere ten years. This rather stark prognosis has spurred discussions and preliminary planning for its eventual replacement. Among the alternatives being seriously considered are ambitious proposals for new tunnels that would bore directly under the [Palisades](/New_Jersey_Palisades), leading straight to the [Lincoln Tunnel](/Lincoln_Tunnel) portals, thus bypassing the aging, spiraling structure entirely. It’s a testament to the enduring human desire to improve, or at least replace, what is undeniably a critical, if aging, piece of infrastructure.

#### North Bergen Viaduct renovation

In June 2018, the [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation) (NJDOT), with a sigh that could almost be heard across the entire state, announced plans for a comprehensive renovation of the North Bergen Viaduct. This section, a crucial elevated roadway, spans over [U.S. Route 1/9](/U.S._Route_1/9) and the persistent [Conrail](/Conrail) rail lines. The project was slated to extend over a period exceeding two years, a timeframe that, for commuters, likely felt more like an eternity. During this period of necessary, yet deeply inconvenient, repair, one travel lane in each direction was to be closed. This effectively reduced the number of operational travel lanes from four to three in each direction, a decision that undoubtedly contributed to the already legendary congestion on [Route 495](/New_Jersey_Route_495). It's a reminder that even the most vital arteries sometimes require invasive surgery, and the patient, in this case, the commuting public, must simply endure.

